<Window x:Class="pls_work.HelpWindow"
        xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
        xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
        xmlns:local="clr-namespace:pls_work"
        xmlns:ui="http://schemas.modernwpf.com/2019"
        ui:WindowHelper.UseModernWindowStyle="True"
        mc:Ignorable="d"
        Title="Help" Height="450" Width="800"
        Closing="Window_Closing">
    <Grid>
        <Label Content="Help" FontFamily="Calibri" FontWeight="UltraLight" FontSize="44" HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="30,21,0,0" VerticalAlignment="Top"/>
        <TextBlock HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="30,111,0,0" FontSize="16" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="225" Width="737">
        Here is a short summary of things you can do in this neat little tool. <LineBreak/><LineBreak/> &#8226; Use the Search bar to look up information from the papers. It can be anything from a keyword to journal name. <LineBreak/> &#8226; Use the Filter button to filter out exactly what you need to look up. <LineBreak/> 
<Bold>Note:</Bold> By default there are only five columns you can see, so check out the filter menu and see all the data we have available for you! <LineBreak/> &#8226; You can click on any of the entries in the table to show a short summary of the paper. At the bottom, you can find the images we found in the paper if you click on the Show Images button, as well as a link to the actual paper itself.
        </TextBlock>
